Consider a toss-up but the Republican candidate is winning the most ground in the final stretch.
A few days before the election, it looks like Laxalt should win this, based on the polling.
Recent polls range from a dead heat (NYT) to Laxalt +4/6. Bumping based on momentum, polls, and predictit (at 80c!)
https://mobile.twitter.com/QuickOne76/status/1586722615112224772

Nevada might be one of the closer elections in a midterm full of close elections. The prediction markets are starting to run towards Laxalt, but the professional forecasters are still very much undecided, with Cook, Inside Elections, and Sabato all rating it as a toss-up. 538 rates it as a dead heat, giving Laxalt (R) the slightest advantage over incumbent Cortez Masto (D). The polls down the stretch are all turning up Laxalt. Anyone looking for a play-by-play account of early voting might want to check out Jon Ralston's work at the Nevada Independent. Early voting is typically not a great indicator of end results, but Ralston has earned a reputation over the years as perhaps the lone accurate reader of the tea leaves. He seemed to give Cortez Masto a better chance than most, but that was before the votes started coming in. We'll see if that holds up. In the meantime, I'm rating his one 55-45 Laxalt.

The Republican candidate is slightly ahead in the polls. Overall each candidate has advantages, which seem to largely cancel out. Combine it with the fact that Nevada is a purple state, I have this as a coin flip.

Laxalt's dad and gramps were both Republican Senators of the olde-tyme grown-up variety--you may remember the type. They knew knew US history, had read the US Constitution, thought the rules meant something, and behaved decently most of the time. It seems young Adam has become a Trumpeter Swain and given up all that. Still, he'll probably win. Maybe he'll shape up once he's in office. Wanna bet?

538 has it on a knife's edge [1] and Trafalgar shows Laxalt up 4% (albeit back in September) [2]. Throw in Nevada aggregate polling with a small Democrat bias in 2020 [3] and I'm comfortable giving Laxalt a small advantage over Cortez Masto.[1] https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2022-election-forecast/senate/nevada/

Dem is leading the finance realm, Republicans already considering it a loss, based on contributions. https://ballotpedia.org/United_States_Senate_election_in_Nevada,_2022
Dem incumbent gives Dems a meaningful shot. But favorable Rep environment gives them a slight edge
Biden's approval rating seems unlikely to recover and the last time a Dem won in a midterm, it was barely so (2018).

I think this will be comfortable Democratic, but no reason to by overly confident this far out. Here's my reasoning: * Democrats have won the last two Senate elections here by thin, but comfortable margins of 5% and ~2%+, the latter by the incumbent, Cortez Maston (CM) in 2016. They also won the governorship by 4% in 2018. * Biden won by a similarly thin but comfortable 2%. I think he wins by closer to 5% if you didn't temporarily have a lot of Nevada voters not living in Nevada. I'm beginning to believe we underestimate the impact of people moving, even temporarily, on closer elections. * Presumptive Republican nominee is currently Adam Laxalt, who last lost a NV statewide election by 4% (the aforementioned governorship race). One reason he lost may be that NV just leans left by about that amount today, but I think he's particularly repulsive to service industry folks due to his opposition to fair wages/overtime. It's a particularly bad look in a state where the service employee's union is so powerful and does turn out the vote.
Go (largely) with the flow.

Although polling is sparse and much could change before Nov, a poll by the Nevada Independent in late January has the Democratic candidate, Mz. Cortes Masto, ahead by 9 points. https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2022/senate/nv/nevada_senate_laxalt_vs_cortez_masto-7392.html

This will be a tough pickup for the Republicans, especially with a Democratic incumbent in the race, but the direction of the midterm elections appears to favor Republicans, and with a strong candidate in the race, assuming he wins the primary, would give the edge to the Republicans, for the moment.
